00:04:10.932 --> 00:04:11.640
This is Paradise.

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:18.140
Mid-morning, the lifeguards
fan across the beach and push

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:21.029
signposts into the sand.

00:04:21.029 --> 00:04:25.310
The same picture is on all of
them-- a stick figure, its arms

00:04:25.310 --> 00:04:30.840
aloft, its circle head drowning
in a set of triangle waves.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:32.980
Caution, the sign reads.

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:35.770
Dangerous undertow.

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:37.320
We ignore it.

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:40.650
We've gone out at Makaha
and Makapu'u before.

00:04:40.650 --> 00:04:43.070
We've felt yokes pull us under.

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:47.470
We are not afraid of the beaches
and breaks here in Waikiki.

00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:50.350
We are careless,
in fact, brazen.

00:04:50.350 --> 00:04:52.780
So when we see her
studying the warning,

00:04:52.780 --> 00:04:55.920
chewing the right side
of her lip, we laugh.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:56.980
Just like the kind.

00:04:56.980 --> 00:04:59.180
Tourists, yeah?

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:01.080
The tourist girl is white.

00:05:01.080 --> 00:05:03.670
They're all white to us
unless they're black.

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:07.170
She has light brown hair,
a pointed nose, eyebrows

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:09.920
neatly plucked into a firm line.

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:13.910
She wears a white bikini with
red polka dots, triangle cut

00:05:13.910 --> 00:05:16.000
top, ruffled bottom.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.150
We shake our heads at her.

00:05:18.150 --> 00:05:21.230
Our ehu hair, pulled
into pony tails,

00:05:21.230 --> 00:05:23.210
bounces against our necks.

00:05:23.210 --> 00:05:26.140
Our bikinis are
carefully cut pieces

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:29.110
with cross back straps
and lean bottoms.

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:31.350
We surf in these, sista.

00:05:31.350 --> 00:05:34.760
We don't have time for
ruffles and ruching.

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:36.060
But she does.

00:05:36.060 --> 00:05:39.630
Like every other tourist, her
blue and white striped hotel

00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:43.630
towel labels for what she is.

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:46.670
So why do we look
at her as we pass?

00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:50.670
Why do we notice her out
of the hundreds of others?

00:05:50.670 --> 00:05:56.540
Do we already know she's
marked, special in some way?

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:59.720
At the high tide line,
[? Cora ?] Jones and [? Kyla ?]

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:02.550
[? Ka'ava ?] pull on rash guards
to protect against the trade

00:06:02.550 --> 00:06:05.240
winds which are
wailing this morning.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:08.300
The rest of us pretend we
don't have chicken skin.

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:10.570
We strap our leashes
to our ankles,

00:06:10.570 --> 00:06:12.820
careful to piece
the Velcro together,

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:15.180
and then we jump on
our boards and feel

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:18.780
them skim across the
surface of the water.

00:06:18.780 --> 00:06:23.010
Arching our backs, our hips
pressed into hard fiberglass,

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:25.520
we dig the water with our hands.

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:28.200
We raise one foot for balance.

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:30.430
And because we know
we are silhouetted

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:33.200
against the horizon,
we hold our heads high.

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:35.090
We point our toes.

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:39.500
Our bodies curve upward like
smiles, beckoning those onshore

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:41.700
to follow.

00:06:41.700 --> 00:06:44.180
When we look back,
the tourist girl

00:06:44.180 --> 00:06:46.760
is approaching the ocean's edge.

00:06:46.760 --> 00:06:50.170
She walks into the water,
the small waves lapping

00:06:50.170 --> 00:06:54.730
at her feet, ankles,
knees, chest.

00:06:54.730 --> 00:06:58.710
We see her dip her shoulders
into the white wash.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:01.830
We don't tell her to stay
away from the retaining wall

00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:04.770
in front of [? Baby ?] Queens
or that today the current is

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:07.890
moving [? Eva ?]
to Diamond Head.

00:07:07.890 --> 00:07:08.930
We paddle.

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:11.705
And in a moment,
we've left her behind.

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:21.780
That story is told by
three groups of women.

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:24.800
The surfer girls,
who you just heard,

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:28.890
hotel housekeepers from the
Federated States of Micronesia,

00:07:28.890 --> 00:07:31.890
and Hawaiian career women.

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:34.580
Their voices weave
together, circle one

00:07:34.580 --> 00:07:38.270
another, much like
a Greek chorus.

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:41.960
My goal was, from the start,
to reorient the reader.

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:44.740
To unsettle them, perhaps.

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:48.700
But to force the reader to see
Waikiki, the ultimate tourist

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:51.225
Shangri-La, from a
native perspective.

00:07:56.230 --> 00:08:00.150
In school, the world
map that usually gets

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:02.620
taught is the one
you can see here.

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:06.810
Centered on the Atlantic
Ocean, on the land masses

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:09.080
that surround it.

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:14.490
In it, the Pacific is cut in
two, pushed to the periphery,

00:08:14.490 --> 00:08:17.520
made to half, not whole.

00:08:23.120 --> 00:08:28.080
Here is a Pacific-centered
world in which

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:33.820
the great, really seafaring
nation of Oceania,

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:34.649
takes center stage.

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:46.010
Another map familiar to most
of you-- the United States.

00:08:46.010 --> 00:08:48.220
No tribal lands delineated.

00:08:48.220 --> 00:08:49.760
No Hawai'i or Alaska.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:55.130
This one's fun to
me because Hawai'i

00:08:55.130 --> 00:08:56.360
is in the Gulf of Mexico.

00:09:03.350 --> 00:09:09.040
And here I like to call it Boxed
Hawai'i overlaid on Mexico.

00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:11.190
And then in the
bottom, this second one

00:09:11.190 --> 00:09:14.100
is what I like to call
Oddly Vertical Hawai'i.

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:15.810
It's not even
oriented correctly.

00:09:19.671 --> 00:09:20.170
OK.

00:09:20.170 --> 00:09:23.350
Here we are back at Oceania.

00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:28.150
These maps and this
geography is how children

00:09:28.150 --> 00:09:30.540
are taught about the US.

00:09:30.540 --> 00:09:33.260
And I don't need to press
too hard on this point,

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:35.530
because I know
everyone here realizes

00:09:35.530 --> 00:09:38.400
just what a falsity that is.

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:39.690
What a lie it is.

00:09:39.690 --> 00:09:46.290
That these are the borders
that we teach to our children

00:09:46.290 --> 00:09:46.920
is a problem.

00:09:53.130 --> 00:09:56.870
The Pacific writer,
anthropologist,

00:09:56.870 --> 00:10:01.550
wonderful thinker, Epeli
Hau'ofa in his paper

00:10:01.550 --> 00:10:04.870
"Our Sea of Islands" says,
"There is a gulf of difference

00:10:04.870 --> 00:10:08.530
between viewing the Pacific
as islands in a far sea

00:10:08.530 --> 00:10:10.960
and as a sea of islands."

00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:15.680
He goes on to argue for
the largesse of Oceania.

00:10:15.680 --> 00:10:20.880
He calls it, in fact, the
largest nation in the world.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:25.940
And he thinks of all the
people within Oceania

00:10:25.940 --> 00:10:28.770
as a single seafaring nation.

00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:30.470
And so it's a
really powerful way

00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:34.685
to think about what happens when
we bring our energies together.

00:10:40.002 --> 00:10:41.460
I'm going to give
you just two more

00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:45.010
slides to think about as I
move into the rest of my talk.

00:10:45.010 --> 00:10:49.430
This first notes
some false dualities,

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:54.390
ways of very often
indigenous people are taught.

00:10:54.390 --> 00:11:01.020
They are romantic or tragic,
scientific or traditional.

00:11:01.020 --> 00:11:07.660
It tends to be whites get
history, and we get culture.

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:10.850
Our record is one that
is oral, but not written.

00:11:15.240 --> 00:11:18.700
And the final slide
I'll linger on

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:22.590
is a Hawaiian word-- mo'olelo.

00:11:22.590 --> 00:11:26.070
It encompasses a
lot, and it breaks up

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:28.400
those false dualities.

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:34.890
It means story, history,
tradition, legend, yarn, a log.

00:11:34.890 --> 00:11:39.360
It means research, public
record, private journal.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:41.410
It also means the
succession of a talk.

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:47.080
Because we're at
Harvard, I'm going

00:11:47.080 --> 00:11:49.340
to tell you a little
bit about my education

00:11:49.340 --> 00:11:50.890
and how I became a writer.

00:11:50.890 --> 00:11:52.720
And it relates
back to the slides

00:11:52.720 --> 00:11:54.480
I showed you at the
beginning and how

00:11:54.480 --> 00:11:55.670
we think about pedagogy.

00:11:58.310 --> 00:12:00.570
You know, when an
undergraduate here tells me

00:12:00.570 --> 00:12:02.830
they go to school
in Cambridge, I

00:12:02.830 --> 00:12:05.480
know they're really
talking about Harvard.

00:12:05.480 --> 00:12:08.680
So similarly, I went to
college in New Jersey.

00:12:12.870 --> 00:12:18.550
And at this New Jersey school,
I had a really mixed experience.

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:21.030
It opened my world
in a lot of ways.

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:23.590
It was like living
in a foreign country.

00:12:23.590 --> 00:12:27.390
There was a new language to
speak, a new fashion to wear,

00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:29.930
and there was a different
way of even physically moving

00:12:29.930 --> 00:12:32.720
through space.

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:34.580
I read a ton in those years.

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:38.760
I was assigned brilliant
work-- Russian novelists,

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:41.920
French poets, good stuff.

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:43.780
And at some point in
my sophomore year,

00:12:43.780 --> 00:12:47.140
I read Edward Sayyid's
"Orientalism", and the idea

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:50.660
of the gaze and of
reversing the gaze became

00:12:50.660 --> 00:12:52.890
one of the first moments
where I felt like I

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:56.250
was glimpsing myself in a text.

00:12:56.250 --> 00:12:59.300
Perhaps I was already
offstage, but I knew

00:12:59.300 --> 00:13:02.780
I had been there a moment ago.

00:13:02.780 --> 00:13:04.440
I majored in
comparative literature

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:06.990
with a focus on [INAUDIBLE]
and post-colonial French

00:13:06.990 --> 00:13:11.040
literature, and I minored
in creative writing.

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:17.290
Four years at the number one
university in the nation,

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:21.280
and not once did I read
an indigenous writer.

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:24.160
Not once did I
even hear the names

00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:28.500
Leslie Marmon Silko, N
Scott Momaday, Thomas King.

00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:31.330
And in creative
writing courses, we

00:13:31.330 --> 00:13:34.630
focused on American literature
and the American short story.

00:13:34.630 --> 00:13:37.720
There was gender balance.

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:41.120
There was not racial balance.

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:44.580
Fast forward five years, and I'm
at the University of Michigan

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:46.875
studying in their Master's
of Fine Arts program

00:13:46.875 --> 00:13:48.630
in creative writing.

00:13:48.630 --> 00:13:52.410
I got word that there was
a Pacific Studies program.

00:13:52.410 --> 00:13:55.600
Granted, it was housed in the
American Studies Department,

00:13:55.600 --> 00:13:58.250
which is a little weird
for all of Oceania

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:01.070
to be under the American
Studies umbrella.

00:14:01.070 --> 00:14:03.050
But it did exist.

00:14:03.050 --> 00:14:06.020
I enrolled in Canoe
Cultures with Vicente Diaz.

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:08.060
And for the first
time in my study

00:14:08.060 --> 00:14:10.650
of post-colonial
literature and history,

00:14:10.650 --> 00:14:14.560
the course started with
an indigenous perspective.

00:14:14.560 --> 00:14:18.360
It started with a
chant, a seafaring song

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:21.360
from the island of Pohnpei
in the Federated States

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:24.970
of Micronesia-- Vince's home.

00:14:24.970 --> 00:14:27.440
For the first time, I
was in a classroom that

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:30.440
wasn't post-colonial
but de-colonial,

00:14:30.440 --> 00:14:32.840
where the professor
looked like me,

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:37.560
knew what it was like to be
me, both outsider and insider

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:39.860
to the university
and academic complex.

00:14:42.990 --> 00:14:48.300
He oriented himself to the
ocean instead of to land.

00:14:48.300 --> 00:14:53.630
He grounded himself and
his teaching in Oceania.

00:14:53.630 --> 00:14:57.490
He and others introduced me
to the Great Pacific writers--

00:14:57.490 --> 00:15:00.980
Maori writer Patricia
Grace, Epeli Hau'ofa,

00:15:00.980 --> 00:15:04.470
Hawaiian professor and
historian John Osorio.

00:15:04.470 --> 00:15:09.320
I also read Silko, Momaday,
King, met Phil Deloria,

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:12.730
read Vine Deloria Jr,
Sherman Alexie, Joy Harjo.

00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:14.880
I can go on.

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:18.910
It changed my life, and
it changed my writing.

00:15:18.910 --> 00:15:23.220
I threw out everything I had
written before that class,

00:15:23.220 --> 00:15:26.470
and I started for the first
time in my life writing

00:15:26.470 --> 00:15:28.410
about Hawaii.

00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:31.005
Writing about what it meant
to be Kanaka Maoli but born

00:15:31.005 --> 00:15:32.430
in California.

00:15:32.430 --> 00:15:36.110
To have split my childhood
between continent and island.

00:15:36.110 --> 00:15:40.070
To try and understand why my
dad decided to leave Hawaii.

00:15:40.070 --> 00:15:42.190
And why my uncles
and aunties stayed.

00:15:42.190 --> 00:15:44.410
And what that means
for their children--

00:15:44.410 --> 00:15:48.040
for me and my cousins.

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:50.680
Writing, for me, is
always about a question,

00:15:50.680 --> 00:15:53.550
about what I don't understand.

00:15:53.550 --> 00:15:58.040
I didn't understand, really,
what it meant to be Kanaka.

00:15:58.040 --> 00:15:59.580
I knew what it felt like.

00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:03.740
And what it felt like was
that I was never enough.

00:16:03.740 --> 00:16:08.730
A feeling that had been
emphasized at Princeton.

00:16:08.730 --> 00:16:11.830
I moved to Hawaii after I
graduated from Michigan.

00:16:11.830 --> 00:16:13.570
I lived in Honolulu.

00:16:13.570 --> 00:16:16.270
I flew over to Maui to visit
the family often and see

00:16:16.270 --> 00:16:19.020
my grandmother, who was ill.

00:16:19.020 --> 00:16:21.930
She died a year
after I moved here.

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:24.160
I was in Ohio at
a friend's wedding

00:16:24.160 --> 00:16:27.460
when I got the call
that she had passed.

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:30.060
My family held off the
funeral until my dad

00:16:30.060 --> 00:16:31.670
and I could fly home to them.

00:16:34.230 --> 00:16:38.130
In writing my first
book, This is Paradise,

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:42.200
I was trying to understand what
it meant to be loved that much.

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:44.530
What it meant to
love myself, all

00:16:44.530 --> 00:16:48.440
myself-- my indigenous
self, my hapa self.

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:50.730
I was trying to
understand how, no matter

00:16:50.730 --> 00:16:57.130
how far my dad or I got from
that land, that island, somehow

00:16:57.130 --> 00:17:01.340
it was always waiting for
us, forgiving us, loving us,

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:04.200
and wanting us back.

00:17:04.200 --> 00:17:06.990
And no matter how
often we went back,

00:17:06.990 --> 00:17:10.569
no matter how long I lived
in Honolulu, how I'd always

00:17:10.569 --> 00:17:14.900
be looking over the ocean at
the continent wondering what

00:17:14.900 --> 00:17:16.310
I was missing out on over there.

00:17:18.970 --> 00:17:23.800
Like many indigenous, I realized
I live in a liminal space.

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:26.800
You see the world from
a liminal position.

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:29.630
A world not filled
with dualities,

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:33.120
as many classes on indigenous
peoples will posit.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:37.115
But one in which, as a
contemporary indigenous person,

00:17:37.115 --> 00:17:40.000
I up-end the framework.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:44.520
And I can have all of it--
science, culture, tradition,

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:48.980
technology, past, present,
oral, written, myth, research,

00:17:48.980 --> 00:17:52.780
legend, fact,
story, story, story.

00:17:52.780 --> 00:17:56.510
All of it at the same time.

00:17:56.510 --> 00:18:01.172
For me, storytelling--
mo'olelo-- holds all that.

00:18:04.620 --> 00:18:08.100
To close, I'd like to read
just a couple more paragraphs

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:10.990
from the story
"This is Paradise".

00:18:10.990 --> 00:18:13.260
The excerpt is from
the perspective

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:16.770
of native Hawaiian
career women, and I'd

00:18:16.770 --> 00:18:20.630
like to dedicate
this to Matika here.

00:18:20.630 --> 00:18:23.810
It's hard work to be a leader.

00:18:23.810 --> 00:18:27.940
It's hard, important,
and beautiful work.

00:18:27.940 --> 00:18:31.200
In this passage, there's an
honest moment of exhaustion

00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:33.350
from the narrators.

00:18:33.350 --> 00:18:36.410
But I hope you also get a
sense of their strength,

00:18:36.410 --> 00:18:40.090
their vibrance, and their
unapologetic aliveness.

00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:54.980
Despite our tendency
toward culinary laziness,

00:18:54.980 --> 00:18:59.450
our exhaustion is not allowed
to overtake us this evening.

00:18:59.450 --> 00:19:02.630
Tonight, we are celebrating.

00:19:02.630 --> 00:19:04.390
Laura just submitted
her proposal

00:19:04.390 --> 00:19:07.020
for a LEED certified
resort on Maui,

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:09.810
and we hear her firm
will win the bid.

00:19:09.810 --> 00:19:13.950
Kiana Naone was promoted to
Politics Editor at the Honolulu

00:19:13.950 --> 00:19:15.480
Advertiser.

00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:18.520
And Esther will take the
lead on a high-profile murder

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:22.900
case that all but promises
her making partner in a year.

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:26.200
After years of part-time
jobs, and student loans,

00:19:26.200 --> 00:19:28.900
and late nights with the
desk lamp's yellow light

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:31.350
on our books, we've made it.

00:19:31.350 --> 00:19:33.320
Or we are making it.

00:19:33.320 --> 00:19:38.320
Or we're close to
saying, We will make it.

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:40.360
It doesn't hurt
that were from here.

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:42.460
We are considered
by our peers to be

00:19:42.460 --> 00:19:44.410
local women who've done well.

00:19:44.410 --> 00:19:46.280
Left but come back.

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:48.860
Dedicated their education
and mainland skills

00:19:48.860 --> 00:19:51.090
to putting this island right.

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:54.470
We speak at civic club
gatherings and native rights

00:19:54.470 --> 00:19:55.430
events.

00:19:55.430 --> 00:19:59.040
We are becoming pillars
of the island community.

00:19:59.040 --> 00:20:03.440
We are growing into who
we've always dreamt of being.

00:20:03.440 --> 00:20:07.980
But sometimes, late at night and
alone beneath the hand-stitched

00:20:07.980 --> 00:20:11.950
Hawaiian quilts we can
finally afford to purchase,

00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:14.470
we wished we had followed
our law and grad school

00:20:14.470 --> 00:20:17.890
boyfriends to DC or Chicago.

00:20:17.890 --> 00:20:20.640
We could have foregone
being pillars.

00:20:20.640 --> 00:20:22.730
We could have been
regular women.

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:26.614
I'll leave you there.

00:20:26.614 --> 00:20:37.590
[APPLAUSE]

00:20:37.590 --> 00:20:45.540
-[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:46.770
-Hello, relatives.

00:20:46.770 --> 00:20:50.260
My Lakota name is Walks
with Young People.

00:20:50.260 --> 00:20:54.550
That was given to me by
my elders a few years ago.

00:20:54.550 --> 00:20:56.310
I also go by Frank Waln.

00:20:56.310 --> 00:21:00.320
I am a Sicangu Lakota hip-hop
artist and storyteller

00:21:00.320 --> 00:21:03.410
from the Rosebud
Reservation in South Dakota.

00:21:03.410 --> 00:21:07.650
And I am the product of
amazing Lakota women.

00:21:07.650 --> 00:21:11.280
I was raised by my mother,
Mary Waln, my grandmother,

00:21:11.280 --> 00:21:14.030
Marie Waln, and my aunties in a
small community on the Rosebud

00:21:14.030 --> 00:21:16.200
Reservation in
South Dakota called

00:21:16.200 --> 00:21:17.930
the [? Hidow ?] community.

00:21:17.930 --> 00:21:18.830
It's pretty rural.

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:20.925
It's pretty small,
twenty houses.

00:21:20.925 --> 00:21:24.060
I was born and
raised on a ranch.

00:21:24.060 --> 00:21:27.870
And I have a story to tell you
guys before we get started.

00:21:27.870 --> 00:21:29.490
So I'm a hip-hop
artist, but I think

00:21:29.490 --> 00:21:31.720
like my fellow amazing
panelists here,

00:21:31.720 --> 00:21:34.450
we're all just storytellers
in our own rights

00:21:34.450 --> 00:21:35.780
and our own ways.

00:21:35.780 --> 00:21:39.870
Indigenous people have been the
best storytellers in this world

00:21:39.870 --> 00:21:42.030
for thousands and
thousands of years.

00:21:42.030 --> 00:21:43.720
That's how we're here.

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:45.280
That's how we survived.

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:48.250
That's how we passed on
knowledge-- storytelling.

00:21:48.250 --> 00:21:50.670
So we're just continuing that
tradition through our art

00:21:50.670 --> 00:21:51.879
and what we do.

00:21:51.879 --> 00:21:53.170
So I have a story to start off.

00:21:55.952 --> 00:21:58.990
I was very privileged that
my mother stressed education

00:21:58.990 --> 00:22:01.220
in all forms, learning in
and outside the classroom

00:22:01.220 --> 00:22:02.770
from the time I was little.

00:22:02.770 --> 00:22:04.330
So when I graduated
high school, I

00:22:04.330 --> 00:22:06.220
was the first person
at my high school

00:22:06.220 --> 00:22:08.011
to receive the Gates
Millenium scholarship.

00:22:08.011 --> 00:22:10.160
I was valedictorian, and
I had the opportunity

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:11.327
to go to college.

00:22:11.327 --> 00:22:13.660
Not a lot of people where I'm
from get that opportunity.

00:22:13.660 --> 00:22:15.410
The biggest high school
on our reservation

00:22:15.410 --> 00:22:17.280
has a 75% dropout rate.

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:21.530
Our entire reservation has
an 80% unemployment rate.

00:22:21.530 --> 00:22:24.040
We live in one of the poorest
counties in the country.

00:22:24.040 --> 00:22:27.470
You know, that poverty keeps
us trapped for a reason.

00:22:27.470 --> 00:22:29.620
But I had this opportunity.

00:22:29.620 --> 00:22:32.420
And I first used it to go
study premed at Creighton

00:22:32.420 --> 00:22:33.870
University in Omaha, Nebraska.

00:22:33.870 --> 00:22:34.960
I did that for two years.

00:22:34.960 --> 00:22:38.379
I always knew I wanted to help,
always knew I wanted to heal.

00:22:38.379 --> 00:22:40.670
And the way I saw the world
when I was 18, the only way

00:22:40.670 --> 00:22:42.755
I thought I could do
that was to be a doctor.

00:22:42.755 --> 00:22:44.380
So I did that for
two years, and then I

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:46.980
decided to follow
my passion of music.

00:22:46.980 --> 00:22:47.604
I love music.

00:22:47.604 --> 00:22:49.270
I've been playing
piano since I was six.

00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:52.504
I've been writing, producing,
recording music since I was 15.

00:22:52.504 --> 00:22:54.170
And so I decided to
follow that passion,

00:22:54.170 --> 00:22:55.260
and that took me
to an art school

00:22:55.260 --> 00:22:57.591
in Chicago-- Columbia College--
where I graduated from.

00:22:57.591 --> 00:22:59.340
And the first week I
was there in Chicago,

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:01.490
something happened
that changed my life.

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:03.689
And I think a lot of
the indigenous students

00:23:03.689 --> 00:23:05.730
in this room could probably
relate to this story.

00:23:05.730 --> 00:23:08.530
So I get on the elevator
of the dorm I'm living in,

00:23:08.530 --> 00:23:11.430
and this non-native girl
gets on the elevator with me.

00:23:11.430 --> 00:23:13.222
And I'm living in
downtown Chicago,

00:23:13.222 --> 00:23:15.430
and I'd never even seen a
skyscraper until this point

00:23:15.430 --> 00:23:16.180
in my life.

00:23:16.180 --> 00:23:18.109
Our reservation's the
size of Rhode Island,

00:23:18.109 --> 00:23:19.900
and we have one stoplight
on our whole rez.

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:22.980
[LAUGHTER] So I'm just in shock.

00:23:22.980 --> 00:23:24.420
All types of cultural shock.

00:23:24.420 --> 00:23:27.050
I could relate to
what Tiana was saying.

00:23:27.050 --> 00:23:29.480
It's like you're in
a different place.

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:31.360
Even how you move is different.

00:23:31.360 --> 00:23:33.700
You have to learn how
to move in that space.

00:23:33.700 --> 00:23:35.097
So I'm on this elevator.

00:23:35.097 --> 00:23:37.680
This girl gets on, and she says,
"You have really pretty hair.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:38.263
What are you?"

00:23:38.263 --> 00:23:42.550
[LAUGHTER] I said, "Thank you.

00:23:42.550 --> 00:23:43.930
I'm Lakota.

00:23:43.930 --> 00:23:45.840
I'm Native American."

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:47.090
And she looked at me confused.

00:23:47.090 --> 00:23:49.300
And she said, "You
guys still exist?"

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:50.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:52.520
You know, we laugh,
but there are too

00:23:52.520 --> 00:23:54.730
many college students in
this country that think

00:23:54.730 --> 00:23:56.680
Native Americans are extinct.

00:23:56.680 --> 00:24:01.254
College educated adults
think we don't exist.

00:24:01.254 --> 00:24:02.670
Imagine what that
does to you when

00:24:02.670 --> 00:24:05.620
you're trying to
relearn, remember,

00:24:05.620 --> 00:24:07.770
reconnect to an identity
that the government has

00:24:07.770 --> 00:24:11.730
tried to kill, as we've
been hearing all day.

00:24:11.730 --> 00:24:17.154
It's all sort of confusion,
frustration, anger, pain.

00:24:17.154 --> 00:24:18.820
Also being proud of
where you come from,

00:24:18.820 --> 00:24:20.650
being proud of that culture.

00:24:20.650 --> 00:24:23.510
So I started writing
songs about that.

00:24:23.510 --> 00:24:26.180
And I'll speak a
little bit on why

00:24:26.180 --> 00:24:29.060
I think hip-hop resonates
with so many indigenous youth.

00:24:29.060 --> 00:24:30.770
You know, hip-hop
is a black culture,

00:24:30.770 --> 00:24:33.656
It was born in New York City
out of a time-- the Bronx,

00:24:33.656 --> 00:24:35.280
they were building
the Bronx Expressway

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:36.238
through this community.

00:24:36.238 --> 00:24:37.460
They were displacing people.

00:24:37.460 --> 00:24:38.626
It was violent displacement.

00:24:38.626 --> 00:24:41.130
It was colonialism, basically.

00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:42.410
It was genocide.

00:24:42.410 --> 00:24:44.160
And out of it came
this beautiful culture

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:49.670
of hip-hop-- dance, graffiti,
music, the way they dressed.

00:24:49.670 --> 00:24:51.980
And when we were going
up on the reservation,

00:24:51.980 --> 00:24:56.280
we were-- I grew up
disconnected from my culture.

00:24:56.280 --> 00:24:58.120
I grew up with my hair short.

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:02.190
I grew up not going to ceremony
because my great grandparents

00:25:02.190 --> 00:25:03.800
were the last
people in my family

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:06.890
to be fluent in our language
and to participate in ceremony.

00:25:06.890 --> 00:25:10.650
And where I'm from,
it was illegal.

00:25:10.650 --> 00:25:12.600
Jesuits would patrol
our reservation,

00:25:12.600 --> 00:25:15.180
and if they caught us going into
sweat lodges, singing songs,

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:15.900
they would call the police.

00:25:15.900 --> 00:25:18.790
We would get persecuted, thrown
in insane asylums for Indians.

00:25:18.790 --> 00:25:20.500
They said we were
worshipping the devil.

00:25:20.500 --> 00:25:23.760
So out of that history,
there was a lot of shame

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:26.536
with being Lakota where
I was from growing up.

00:25:26.536 --> 00:25:28.660
There was a lot of shame
with men having long hair.

00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:31.486
There was a lot of shame
about men wearing earrings.

00:25:31.486 --> 00:25:33.860
There was a lot of shame about
being proud of who you are

00:25:33.860 --> 00:25:34.859
and where you come from.

00:25:34.859 --> 00:25:38.030
And I understand where that's
coming from from my elders.

00:25:38.030 --> 00:25:39.767
I understand what
they went through.

00:25:39.767 --> 00:25:41.850
Even though I may never
know what that feels like,

00:25:41.850 --> 00:25:44.030
I understand where
that shame comes from.

00:25:44.030 --> 00:25:47.695
And hip-hop gave me a safe
space to reclaim my indigineity.

00:25:47.695 --> 00:25:49.820
Because the thing about
hip-hop as a culture is you

00:25:49.820 --> 00:25:52.310
can be whoever you want
to be in that space.

00:25:52.310 --> 00:25:54.040
You bring to it who you are.

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:57.360
And so it gave me a space
to look at my own identity.

00:25:57.360 --> 00:25:59.767
And around the same
time I was 18, 19,

00:25:59.767 --> 00:26:02.100
I started reconnecting to my
culture, and my ceremonies,

00:26:02.100 --> 00:26:03.220
and language.

00:26:03.220 --> 00:26:05.710
My mother, my aunties--
they were doing the same.

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:07.620
We were all doing that
around the same time.

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:15.170
And also within hip-hop there's
the tradition of storytelling.

00:26:15.170 --> 00:26:17.700
And that culture was kind
of born out of colonization,

00:26:17.700 --> 00:26:21.050
and so I think it resonated
with a lot of native youth

00:26:21.050 --> 00:26:22.590
all across this country.

00:26:22.590 --> 00:26:24.570
I'm one of many native
hip-hop artists.

00:26:24.570 --> 00:26:26.850
There's tons of
brilliant artists.

00:26:26.850 --> 00:26:29.380
And so I want to talk a
little bit about how art,

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:32.950
how performance gives me
that space to almost rupture,

00:26:32.950 --> 00:26:36.730
and rage, and let some of
that pain, and that energy,

00:26:36.730 --> 00:26:39.280
and those emotions-- the
love, the joy-- everything

00:26:39.280 --> 00:26:42.360
that I'm experiencing
out in a healthy way.

00:26:42.360 --> 00:26:46.340
Because to tell indigenous
people to not be angry,

00:26:46.340 --> 00:26:49.000
to not feel, to
not be frustrated,

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.590
is to tell us to
not be human beings.

00:26:51.590 --> 00:26:54.150
How could we not be angry
about 500 years of colonization

00:26:54.150 --> 00:26:55.189
and genocide?

00:26:55.189 --> 00:26:56.480
How could we not be frustrated?

00:26:56.480 --> 00:26:57.840
How could we not feel pain?

00:26:57.840 --> 00:27:00.048
And it's not just history
that results in the traumas

00:27:00.048 --> 00:27:02.240
that we face.

00:27:02.240 --> 00:27:04.980
The traumas of people that we
love, the own traumas that we

00:27:04.980 --> 00:27:06.660
experience as people.

00:27:06.660 --> 00:27:10.060
So I think I needed
a healthy outlet,

00:27:10.060 --> 00:27:12.320
and this art form have
me that healthy outlet.

00:27:12.320 --> 00:27:16.600
So right now, I'm really
interested in exploring healing

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:18.800
and love through my music.

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:22.470
And Tiana even spoke about that.

00:27:22.470 --> 00:27:24.080
Right now I'm on
artist residency

00:27:24.080 --> 00:27:25.660
at the University of Delaware.

00:27:25.660 --> 00:27:26.860
I'm visiting music classes.

00:27:26.860 --> 00:27:29.050
But I'm also going into
Nemours Children's Hospital,

00:27:29.050 --> 00:27:31.920
which is hospital for children
who are terminally ill.

00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:33.890
And I'm doing music
therapy with kids.

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:36.990
And we've been having
a lot of discussions

00:27:36.990 --> 00:27:41.040
about what gets them through
the situation they're in.

00:27:41.040 --> 00:27:44.450
And one of the most profound
statements and ideas that's

00:27:44.450 --> 00:27:47.430
come out that for me
is the concept of love,

00:27:47.430 --> 00:27:50.410
and that love is the strongest
force in the universe.

00:27:50.410 --> 00:27:52.810
This one girl told me
if you don't have love,

00:27:52.810 --> 00:27:54.580
you don't have anything.

00:27:54.580 --> 00:27:57.080
And I think that all the
indigenous people in this room,

00:27:57.080 --> 00:27:59.110
we are a testament to
the love and strength

00:27:59.110 --> 00:28:00.600
that our ancestors had.

00:28:00.600 --> 00:28:02.760
The fact that we're
even alive in this room

00:28:02.760 --> 00:28:05.980
in a place like Harvard is
a testament to that I love.

00:28:05.980 --> 00:28:06.712
They loved us.

00:28:06.712 --> 00:28:07.670
They loved the culture.

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:08.503
They loved the land.

00:28:08.503 --> 00:28:10.300
They loved the water.

00:28:10.300 --> 00:28:12.130
And that's why we're here.

00:28:12.130 --> 00:28:14.780
So I think about that
when I write these songs.

00:28:14.780 --> 00:28:19.110
Learning to love myself,
learning to love my community.

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:20.611
It's a task.

00:28:20.611 --> 00:28:22.610
I'm probably one of the
youngest panelists here.

00:28:22.610 --> 00:28:25.290
I'm 26, and I'm
going through it.

00:28:25.290 --> 00:28:28.520
Even though I'm here in Harvard,
and I get a travel the world

00:28:28.520 --> 00:28:30.890
and do what I love,
the people I love--

00:28:30.890 --> 00:28:32.150
we're still connected to them.

00:28:32.150 --> 00:28:34.580
My mom is still at home
suffering from poverty.

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:36.760
I have cousins addicted in meth.

00:28:36.760 --> 00:28:37.540
This is real.

00:28:37.540 --> 00:28:39.380
This isn't just history for us.

00:28:39.380 --> 00:28:40.884
This pain is real.

00:28:40.884 --> 00:28:42.300
And I've found
that when I've been

00:28:42.300 --> 00:28:44.560
able to express this
and write this in songs,

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:47.390
my outlet has become an inlet
for a lot of other indigenous

00:28:47.390 --> 00:28:48.040
people.

00:28:48.040 --> 00:28:49.540
And I never expected
that to happen,

00:28:49.540 --> 00:28:51.940
but it's a really
beautiful thing.

00:28:51.940 --> 00:28:57.790
So I just want to comment on
that concept of love as well

00:28:57.790 --> 00:29:02.470
and say that my grandfather,
Robert [? Sonny ?] Waln,

00:29:02.470 --> 00:29:04.380
he passed away when I was three.

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:07.010
He only had an eighth
grade education.

00:29:07.010 --> 00:29:10.070
He had to drop out
of school at 16

00:29:10.070 --> 00:29:11.970
and lie about his age
to join the military

00:29:11.970 --> 00:29:13.260
to provide for his family.

00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:14.968
Because I come from
a place where there's

00:29:14.968 --> 00:29:16.220
little to no opportunities.

00:29:16.220 --> 00:29:18.000
And that's what he
had to do to survive.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.400
And he went off to the
Korean War for four years.

00:29:20.400 --> 00:29:22.390
Came back, married
my grandmother,

00:29:22.390 --> 00:29:25.560
