super honored to be

00:35:00.040 --> 00:35:04.830
amongst such special, talented,
intelligent, beautiful people.

00:35:04.830 --> 00:35:09.040
I'd like to acknowledge
the ancestors of this land.

00:35:09.040 --> 00:35:12.840
The Massachusett, Nipmuc,
and Wampanoag people.

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:14.915
We raise our hands to you.

00:35:14.915 --> 00:35:15.790
-[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:35:15.790 --> 00:35:19.180
-Thank you for allowing us
to be here on your land.

00:35:19.180 --> 00:35:23.460
And I raise my hands to Miss
Shelley, and Jason, and all

00:35:23.460 --> 00:35:25.790
of the organizers of this
event, and especially

00:35:25.790 --> 00:35:28.800
our young native
students here at Harvard.

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:29.770
We respect you.

00:35:29.770 --> 00:35:30.369
We love you.

00:35:30.369 --> 00:35:31.410
We want you to stay here.

00:35:35.324 --> 00:35:43.370
I'm here to ask you if we can
learn to see as human beings.

00:35:43.370 --> 00:35:47.480
Does the image actually
affect our lives and the lives

00:35:47.480 --> 00:35:49.090
of those around us?

00:35:49.090 --> 00:35:51.830
And as citizens of
the world, can we

00:35:51.830 --> 00:35:57.740
use images to encourage
and inspire one another?

00:35:57.740 --> 00:36:02.190
How can we, my friends,
shape our perceptions

00:36:02.190 --> 00:36:05.160
to change the world?

00:36:05.160 --> 00:36:07.820
Currently, there is
not one single source--

00:36:07.820 --> 00:36:09.730
be it publication,
website, or exhibition--

00:36:09.730 --> 00:36:11.480
accessible to the
public that provides

00:36:11.480 --> 00:36:16.010
visual representation of every
tribe in the United States.

00:36:16.010 --> 00:36:19.700
Project 562 aims to change that.

00:36:19.700 --> 00:36:22.150
Why am I doing this?

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:24.300
I taught visual
arts for five years

00:36:24.300 --> 00:36:27.600
at the tribal school on my rez.

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:31.570
Our children needed effective
curriculums and stories

00:36:31.570 --> 00:36:37.330
that could transmit light,
love, beauty, truth.

00:36:37.330 --> 00:36:38.296
But there wasn't.

00:36:38.296 --> 00:36:40.680
There were none.

00:36:40.680 --> 00:36:46.790
We still teach our children that
Columbus discovered America.

00:36:46.790 --> 00:36:49.080
The American
imagination produces

00:36:49.080 --> 00:36:54.890
leathered and feathered,
savagery, less than.

00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:58.570
The toll of addiction,
abuse, and unnatural deaths

00:36:58.570 --> 00:37:02.970
of my students overwhelmed me.

00:37:02.970 --> 00:37:06.635
I buried 19 students
in four years.

00:37:09.420 --> 00:37:12.870
And after so much
loss of potential,

00:37:12.870 --> 00:37:16.230
I'd sit in lodges with
my fellow teachers,

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:19.970
and we'd be sitting there
praying for our babies,

00:37:19.970 --> 00:37:24.810
begging the Creator to help
us, feeling a hopelessness

00:37:24.810 --> 00:37:29.710
and despair that I can
barely speak about.

00:37:29.710 --> 00:37:33.090
These are the images
that we seen when were

00:37:33.090 --> 00:37:35.960
represented in massive media.

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:42.230
This is the experience that our
children are having every day.

00:37:42.230 --> 00:37:46.460
Native American stereotypes
are ingrained in the fabric

00:37:46.460 --> 00:37:51.260
of our country, as historical
people, as tribal and inferior.

00:37:51.260 --> 00:37:53.970
Most contemporary depictions
of Native Americans

00:37:53.970 --> 00:37:58.210
include noble savage, redskins,
leathered and feathered,

00:37:58.210 --> 00:38:00.690
spiritual being as
fit for mascots.

00:38:00.690 --> 00:38:04.570
And such portrayals degrade
popular understanding.

00:38:04.570 --> 00:38:07.130
This is what happens when
you Google search Native

00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:09.300
American this morning.

00:38:09.300 --> 00:38:12.570
This algorithm represents
the image people are seeking,

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:19.880
and the image that
people are clicking on.

00:38:19.880 --> 00:38:24.810
This is what you expect when
you search Native American.

00:38:24.810 --> 00:38:28.300
My mentor, Stephanie
[? Freiberg ?]--

00:38:28.300 --> 00:38:30.766
She doesn't know
she's my mentor.

00:38:30.766 --> 00:38:33.140
I call her that because I've
read everything she's wrote,

00:38:33.140 --> 00:38:35.056
she's from my tribe, and
I secretly stalk her.

00:38:35.056 --> 00:38:38.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:38.010 --> 00:38:39.471
She did this incredible study.

00:38:39.471 --> 00:38:41.470
She went to all these
tribes around the country.

00:38:41.470 --> 00:38:44.570
She showed kids pictures
of Native American,

00:38:44.570 --> 00:38:46.350
African American,
Asian American.

00:38:46.350 --> 00:38:49.010
And every time they were shown
an image of a native person,

00:38:49.010 --> 00:38:53.080
their self-esteem
went down by 60%.

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:55.510
Shockingly, when the
image of an Indian

00:38:55.510 --> 00:38:57.420
is shown to the
white counterpart,

00:38:57.420 --> 00:39:01.000
their self-esteem is raised.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:06.470
For centuries, our people have
called for authentic indigenous

00:39:06.470 --> 00:39:09.310
images and stories
of our resiliency,

00:39:09.310 --> 00:39:12.710
of the sacredness of
land, of the meaning

00:39:12.710 --> 00:39:15.610
and value of our knowledge.

00:39:15.610 --> 00:39:18.120
These are the stories
and so many more

00:39:18.120 --> 00:39:21.030
that live within Project 562.

00:39:21.030 --> 00:39:27.880
And they're the voices that can
now be heard if we seek them.

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:29.040
Like this one.

00:39:29.040 --> 00:39:31.440
This is Uncle John
[? Kakeana'ana. ?]

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:35.650
He's Kanaka Maoli from the
Independent Nation of Hawai'i.

00:39:35.650 --> 00:39:38.560
John is pictured on
the west side of Kuai'i

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:41.130
at his kalo farm that
has been in his family

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:42.690
for several generations.

00:39:42.690 --> 00:39:45.960
To John and other
kanaka maolis, kalo

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:51.230
is of supreme importance--
defined in the Kumulipo,

00:39:51.230 --> 00:39:55.750
or Hawaiian creation chant, as
the plant from which Hawaiians

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:57.130
were formed.

00:39:57.130 --> 00:39:59.840
In 2002, into the
University of Hawaii

00:39:59.840 --> 00:40:04.620
genetically modified kalo and
patented their hybridized taro,

00:40:04.620 --> 00:40:08.180
charging farmers for
the new type of seed.

00:40:08.180 --> 00:40:13.720
John was a part of a strong
indigenous opposition

00:40:13.720 --> 00:40:17.480
and coalitions and
peaceful protests

00:40:17.480 --> 00:40:22.870
to protect the
natural, ancestral kalo

00:40:22.870 --> 00:40:26.260
And through his activism
and many others,

00:40:26.260 --> 00:40:31.000
in 2008 the state of
Hawaii designated kalo

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:36.640
as a state plant in a bill to
ban genetically modified taro

00:40:36.640 --> 00:40:38.885
and coffee in the
islands of Hawaii.

00:40:38.885 --> 00:40:44.730
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:44.730 --> 00:40:47.680
Over and over, and over
again, people ask me,

00:40:47.680 --> 00:40:50.876
What is the greatest lesson
that you've learned, Matika?

00:40:50.876 --> 00:40:52.750
What have you learned
from being on the road?

00:40:52.750 --> 00:40:56.290
And I often respond by
saying, The only thing

00:40:56.290 --> 00:40:59.860
I've fully come to understand
is that our people's identities

00:40:59.860 --> 00:41:02.870
are inextricably
connected to the land.

00:41:02.870 --> 00:41:05.730
We are the people of
the blue green water,

00:41:05.730 --> 00:41:11.000
the people of the tide, the
people of the tall pine trees,

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:12.880
the people that
live within the four

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:15.740
sacred mountains, the people
of the streaming tide.

00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:18.890
We're the rabbit eaters,
the cattails eaters.

00:41:18.890 --> 00:41:20.810
We're the people
of the longhouse.

00:41:20.810 --> 00:41:24.390
There is an indigenous
people of this place as well.

00:41:24.390 --> 00:41:28.920
And what we see overwhelmingly
is that our communities

00:41:28.920 --> 00:41:32.310
are always fighting
for the right

00:41:32.310 --> 00:41:37.650
to maintain access to the
very thing that defines us.

00:41:37.650 --> 00:41:40.980
Such as this fellow
this is Raymond Matts.

00:41:40.980 --> 00:41:43.054
He's one of my heroes.

00:41:43.054 --> 00:41:44.720
And you see, he's not
smiling because he

00:41:44.720 --> 00:41:49.070
has all gold busted teeth
because the cops punched them

00:41:49.070 --> 00:41:51.660
all out while he
was being arrested

00:41:51.660 --> 00:41:56.120
19 times for fishing on the
Klamath River in California.

00:41:56.120 --> 00:41:58.950
He belongs to the Yurok tribe,
and he was one of the first

00:41:58.950 --> 00:42:02.230
to challenge the US government
for tribal fishing rights.

00:42:02.230 --> 00:42:04.930
He brought his case all the
way to the Supreme Court,

00:42:04.930 --> 00:42:07.930
and he recalls the turning
point in that case,

00:42:07.930 --> 00:42:11.810
as maybe some of you do as well.

00:42:11.810 --> 00:42:15.730
He says, we'd laid
out our set nets.

00:42:15.730 --> 00:42:18.550
And from this rock
here, where their people

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:21.910
have been fishing for thousands
of generations, and the feds

00:42:21.910 --> 00:42:24.450
were there with
big, enormous guns

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:26.180
waiting for them to
go pick their net.

00:42:26.180 --> 00:42:28.290
And they were kind of
a little apprehensive.

00:42:28.290 --> 00:42:29.150
They didn't know what to do.

00:42:29.150 --> 00:42:31.233
They knew that if they
went out to pick their net,

00:42:31.233 --> 00:42:32.950
they'd be forcefully
arrested again.

00:42:32.950 --> 00:42:37.580
And for Mr. Matts, that would
be his last time being arrested.

00:42:37.580 --> 00:42:40.750
And so there's a lot of
commotion on the shores.

00:42:40.750 --> 00:42:44.840
And finally, after a three-day
standoff, and reporters

00:42:44.840 --> 00:42:49.110
there as well, his 89-year-old
grandma said, Enough of this.

00:42:49.110 --> 00:42:51.720
I'll do it.

00:42:51.720 --> 00:42:54.730
And so she got in
her little canoe,

00:42:54.730 --> 00:42:59.500
and she started paddling out
there, and picking the net.

00:42:59.500 --> 00:43:05.440
And of course, cops came
and by gunpoint demand

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:06.570
that she stop poaching.

00:43:09.980 --> 00:43:14.660
They took pictures, went on
the cover of Time magazine.

00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:18.470
They won their court case, which
set precedence for the Judge

00:43:18.470 --> 00:43:22.800
Bolt decision which gave
tribes half the fish,

00:43:22.800 --> 00:43:26.602
and game, and wildlife, and
co-management of our resources.

00:43:26.602 --> 00:43:28.685
And you see, my momma is
a commercial fisherwoman.

00:43:31.420 --> 00:43:36.080
And I was super, super honored
to have the opportunity

00:43:36.080 --> 00:43:39.230
to thank Raymond
for his bravery,

00:43:39.230 --> 00:43:42.860
for being brave enough to stand
for what matters to us most.

00:43:45.900 --> 00:43:48.770
This is miss Jenny Parker.

00:43:48.770 --> 00:43:52.600
She was a teacher for 25
years in her tribal school

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:56.750
in northern Cheyenne
until one day,

00:43:56.750 --> 00:44:00.150
federal officials came to
her at the school and said,

00:44:00.150 --> 00:44:04.390
We'd like you to come
down and identify a body.

00:44:04.390 --> 00:44:06.610
It was her daughter's.

00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:08.911
She'd been forcefully
raped and left for dead

00:44:08.911 --> 00:44:09.910
on the side of the road.

00:44:13.120 --> 00:44:15.900
And afterwards, Jenny
had a heart attack.

00:44:15.900 --> 00:44:20.560
She felt as though she was
dying of a broken heart.

00:44:20.560 --> 00:44:23.910
And her granddaughter
came and said, Grandmama,

00:44:23.910 --> 00:44:25.907
I'll take care of you.

00:44:25.907 --> 00:44:28.240
Slowly, they started walking
to the end of the driveway,

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:29.198
to the end of the road.

00:44:29.198 --> 00:44:32.190
And Jenny says, It's
the love that helped

00:44:32.190 --> 00:44:33.990
her to survive such things.

00:44:33.990 --> 00:44:37.970
It's knowing that her
granddaughter would need her.

00:44:37.970 --> 00:44:39.520
And I asked Jenny,
What would you

00:44:39.520 --> 00:44:42.420
like me to tell the people
when I show your photograph?

00:44:42.420 --> 00:44:48.650
And she said, Ask them
if they'll stand with us.

00:44:48.650 --> 00:44:52.470
Ask them if it matters to them.

00:44:52.470 --> 00:44:57.110
Remind them that
we're still here.

00:44:57.110 --> 00:44:59.090
I want to stand up
here and tell you

00:44:59.090 --> 00:45:02.150
transcendent stories of
light, and love, and beauty.

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:05.970
But as my friends say,
If you want our beauty,

00:45:05.970 --> 00:45:09.460
you must also take our struggle.

00:45:09.460 --> 00:45:14.790
The truth is, I have heard far
too many stories like Jenny's.

00:45:14.790 --> 00:45:17.370
Stories about forced
sterilization,

00:45:17.370 --> 00:45:21.650
stories of rape and horror
that at times make me

00:45:21.650 --> 00:45:26.160
feel like I'm suffocating
and like there

00:45:26.160 --> 00:45:30.140
is no hope in Indian country.

00:45:30.140 --> 00:45:34.070
And these experiences articulate
our current socioeconomic

00:45:34.070 --> 00:45:35.390
situation.

00:45:35.390 --> 00:45:39.350
Native American women are the
most victimized in the country.

00:45:39.350 --> 00:45:41.130
Three out of four
have experienced

00:45:41.130 --> 00:45:45.600
sexual assault or domestic
violence in their lifetimes.

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:50.610
And that's my sisters,
my aunties, my cousins,

00:45:50.610 --> 00:45:53.420
the native women in this room.

00:45:53.420 --> 00:45:54.170
It's real.

00:45:57.210 --> 00:46:04.381
And for most native women, it is
not a question of if but when.

00:46:07.190 --> 00:46:09.560
Across the border
in Canada, there

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:14.300
are an estimated
1,181 stolen sisters--

00:46:14.300 --> 00:46:17.590
women from age two to 78
disappeared and never found,

00:46:17.590 --> 00:46:19.210
missing and likely murdered.

00:46:19.210 --> 00:46:22.600
There is no question we
are in a very critical time

00:46:22.600 --> 00:46:25.150
of a longstanding epidemic
of abuse and misuse

00:46:25.150 --> 00:46:26.780
of our Native
women and children.

00:46:26.780 --> 00:46:30.040
And while our women tell me
stories about race, and caste,

00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:33.000
and how their bodies are
used to perpetuate both,

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:36.990
high caste women are sexually
restricted-- reserved,

00:46:36.990 --> 00:46:41.980
if you will-- while women at the
bottom are sexually exploited.

00:46:41.980 --> 00:46:43.980
Native people are
the only people

00:46:43.980 --> 00:46:47.100
in the country that need
prove their pedigree.

00:46:47.100 --> 00:46:50.320
Still today, we faced
extermination policies

00:46:50.320 --> 00:46:53.220
put in place to eradicate
the American Indian.

00:46:53.220 --> 00:46:55.760
Which means that
as a native woman,

00:46:55.760 --> 00:46:58.980
we are faced with the complicity
of choosing a mate when

00:46:58.980 --> 00:47:03.050
race's policies determine our
future children's opportunity

00:47:03.050 --> 00:47:05.390
for citizenship and inclusion.

00:47:05.390 --> 00:47:08.556
We're forced in courts
to define ourselves.

00:47:11.460 --> 00:47:14.740
It's time we take back the
right to make decisions

00:47:14.740 --> 00:47:16.860
about ourselves.

00:47:16.860 --> 00:47:19.630
A lesson I've learned from a
well-known leader in my own

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:21.565
could tribal community,
Miss Deborah Parker.

00:47:24.380 --> 00:47:25.560
Part of Miss Deborah Parker.

00:47:25.560 --> 00:47:28.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:28.390 --> 00:47:30.806
-That was about to be
so smooth, though, huh?

00:47:30.806 --> 00:47:34.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:34.130 --> 00:47:38.040
-If you go to the
gallery, you could see it.

00:47:38.040 --> 00:47:41.460
Who advocated on behalf of
native women during the right

00:47:41.460 --> 00:47:43.460
to reauthorize the
Violence Against Women Act,

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:46.140
and while also running a
program in our community

00:47:46.140 --> 00:47:49.070
to help our victimized
and abused people.

00:47:49.070 --> 00:47:51.380
When I ask her where
she finds strength,

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:57.520
she said, When you are
asked to protect someone,

00:47:57.520 --> 00:48:02.110
when you are asked to protect
your nation, it's what you do.

00:48:02.110 --> 00:48:04.000
You armor up.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:08.340
You warrior up, and you protect
the women in your nation.

00:48:08.340 --> 00:48:11.400
And it's a great honor to do so.

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:16.250
All I can do is pray that
I am able to speak justice

00:48:16.250 --> 00:48:19.150
toward our missing and
murdered indigenous woman,

00:48:19.150 --> 00:48:21.140
to those who are
still here struggling

00:48:21.140 --> 00:48:24.290
to find out what kind of
justice they will receive.

00:48:24.290 --> 00:48:27.260
To me, it will be a
lifetime of this work.

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:31.250
It will never stop, because
every man and woman is worth

00:48:31.250 --> 00:48:33.090
protecting.

00:48:33.090 --> 00:48:35.700
Every person deserves justice.

00:48:42.180 --> 00:48:45.550
We can do that
through education.

00:48:45.550 --> 00:48:47.540
This is Dr. Mary
Evelyn Belgarde.

00:48:47.540 --> 00:48:49.830
She's from the Pueblo of
Isleta and Ohkay Owingeh.

00:48:49.830 --> 00:48:52.540
She's a retired Professor of
Education for the University

00:48:52.540 --> 00:48:53.140
of New Mexico.

00:48:53.140 --> 00:48:56.620
She's worked tirelessly
to open tribal schools

00:48:56.620 --> 00:48:58.880
with native curriculums.

00:48:58.880 --> 00:49:02.560
She's raised funds to support
thousands of native students.

00:49:02.560 --> 00:49:03.850
And she's lovely.

00:49:03.850 --> 00:49:04.610
She's charming.

00:49:04.610 --> 00:49:08.040
She feeds you green chili.

00:49:08.040 --> 00:49:10.160
And then she want to
talk about systematically

00:49:10.160 --> 00:49:12.630
engineered systems of
education to eradicate us.

00:49:12.630 --> 00:49:14.830
And she says,
Matika, when are we

00:49:14.830 --> 00:49:17.360
going to stop asking
our children to choose

00:49:17.360 --> 00:49:20.650
between cultural education
and Western education?

00:49:20.650 --> 00:49:23.180
I think we're ready to stop
the assimilation process.

00:49:23.180 --> 00:49:26.540
The time to change is now.

00:49:26.540 --> 00:49:28.922
This is-- this is not.

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:33.000
Oh.

00:49:35.780 --> 00:49:38.270
Dr. Adrian King, could
you stand up please?

00:49:38.270 --> 00:49:40.200
Everybody look back here.

00:49:40.200 --> 00:49:42.120
This is Dr. Adrian King.

00:49:42.120 --> 00:49:45.900
[APPLAUSE]

00:49:45.900 --> 00:49:48.850
-I have a beautiful
photo of her.

00:49:48.850 --> 00:49:53.600
And let me tell you, she is my
favorite Cherokee of all time.

00:49:53.600 --> 00:49:55.540
And she's a dear friend
of mine, and you'll

00:49:55.540 --> 00:49:58.020
be hearing from her
later this afternoon.

00:49:58.020 --> 00:50:01.740
You don't have to
keep standing, Adrian.

00:50:01.740 --> 00:50:05.120
But I would like to acknowledge
that Adrian is one of the few

00:50:05.120 --> 00:50:08.674
that holds a doctorate in
education from Harvard.

00:50:08.674 --> 00:50:11.850
And she's currently
teaching at Brown,

00:50:11.850 --> 00:50:14.670
and focuses on college
access for native students.

00:50:14.670 --> 00:50:16.620
Her blog, Native
Appropriations, has

00:50:16.620 --> 00:50:19.080
a national and
international audience.

00:50:19.080 --> 00:50:21.920
As a voice on contemporary
indigenous issues,

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:25.310
she writes about the
collectivism of native students

00:50:25.310 --> 00:50:26.510
in higher education.

00:50:26.510 --> 00:50:29.270
And she says, I want
to take a moment

00:50:29.270 --> 00:50:33.160
to talk to your family, your
professors, your community,

00:50:33.160 --> 00:50:35.900
your school administrators.

00:50:35.900 --> 00:50:40.320
We have a responsibility
to our native students.

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:43.840
It is not enough to push
students to enroll in college

00:50:43.840 --> 00:50:46.180
and expect them to
conform to the norms

00:50:46.180 --> 00:50:52.860
and expectations of spaces
that are not meant for them

00:50:52.860 --> 00:50:56.630
and then forge
their own path home.

00:50:56.630 --> 00:51:00.220
We need to embody the
Cherokee concept of gadugi,

00:51:00.220 --> 00:51:03.940
working together toward
a common goal that

00:51:03.940 --> 00:51:06.690
benefits the entire community.

00:51:06.690 --> 00:51:09.440
This is Miss Helen.

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:10.210
She's blind.

00:51:10.210 --> 00:51:13.250
She's the last Lovelock
Paiute speaker.

00:51:13.250 --> 00:51:16.640
I just recently went
to meet with her.

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:19.890
All around Indian country,
our indigenous languages

00:51:19.890 --> 00:51:22.000
are at risk of being lost.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:26.430
I can't tell you how many
women I've met like Miss Helen.

00:51:26.430 --> 00:51:29.700
Man, I had this dream.

00:51:29.700 --> 00:51:32.670
I was on a subway
in Seattle, which

00:51:32.670 --> 00:51:36.020
is how I knew I was dreaming.

00:51:36.020 --> 00:51:39.750
And there was people to
my left arguing in Lakota

00:51:39.750 --> 00:51:42.260
about Trump and Barack Obama.

00:51:42.260 --> 00:51:45.330
And there was people to my
right eating fast food--

00:51:45.330 --> 00:51:49.330
wild Anishinaabe rice--
speaking in Anishinaabe

00:51:49.330 --> 00:51:51.790
about changing the
local downtown scene.

00:51:51.790 --> 00:51:53.930
And there was people
talking in the Dene

00:51:53.930 --> 00:51:57.180
about changing our education
system so that everybody

00:51:57.180 --> 00:51:58.950
would speak Dene.

00:51:58.950 --> 00:52:03.800
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:03.800 --> 00:52:12.150
And you know, I
woke up in tears.

00:52:12.150 --> 00:52:15.286
Because I thought to myself,
It's never going to happen.

00:52:18.570 --> 00:52:24.920
And then I had to like
smudge myself off and realize

00:52:24.920 --> 00:52:26.450
that if I don't
believe that it's

00:52:26.450 --> 00:52:28.830
possible for our white
brothers and sisters

00:52:28.830 --> 00:52:31.410
to learn our languages,
for our own people

00:52:31.410 --> 00:52:34.930
to establish systems where
we can relearn our languages,

00:52:34.930 --> 00:52:37.640
for us to actually
acknowledge that there

00:52:37.640 --> 00:52:41.870
is an indigenous land,
history, intelligence that

00:52:41.870 --> 00:52:46.170
is here and among us that
is worth saving, protecting,

00:52:46.170 --> 00:52:48.240
and learning.

00:52:48.240 --> 00:52:50.180
If I don't believe
that, then who will?

00:52:53.210 --> 00:52:55.739
Three years ago-- I'm
almost done, I promise.

00:52:55.739 --> 00:52:56.530
I'm sorry, Shelley.

00:52:56.530 --> 00:52:57.290
One minute.

00:52:57.290 --> 00:52:59.430
Three years ago, I left
my job, family, and home

00:52:59.430 --> 00:53:01.360
to begin traveling
for Project 562,

00:53:01.360 --> 00:53:03.640
a multi-year creative
expedition dedicated

00:53:03.640 --> 00:53:07.140
to photographing over 562
federally recognized tribes

00:53:07.140 --> 00:53:08.250
in the Unite States.

00:53:08.250 --> 00:53:12.970
To date, I have traveled to
over 250 tribes in 47 states,

00:53:12.970 --> 00:53:15.250
taking nearly 800
portraits and collecting

00:53:15.250 --> 00:53:18.700
each person's history.

00:53:18.700 --> 00:53:22.770
I realize, to some, that
this is very radical.

00:53:22.770 --> 00:53:25.710
And rad young folks
of Harvard, before I

00:53:25.710 --> 00:53:28.150
say anything else about the
purpose of today's lecture,

00:53:28.150 --> 00:53:29.440
let me say this.

00:53:29.440 --> 00:53:31.730
I hope that the stories that
I've shared with you will

00:53:31.730 --> 00:53:34.720
you inspire you to
go on an adventure.

00:53:34.720 --> 00:53:37.380
Especially for you young ladies.

00:53:37.380 --> 00:53:39.560
I read something of
Gloria Steinem's newest

00:53:39.560 --> 00:53:41.230
novel that rocked my world.

00:53:41.230 --> 00:53:44.740
She said, Thanks to
molecular archeology, which

00:53:44.740 --> 00:53:46.380
includes the study
of ancient DNA

00:53:46.380 --> 00:53:48.130
to trace human
movement over time,

00:53:48.130 --> 00:53:52.640
we now know that men have
been the stay-at-homes,

00:53:52.640 --> 00:53:55.060
and women have
been the travelers.

00:53:55.060 --> 00:53:57.260
The rate of intercontinental
migration for women

00:53:57.260 --> 00:53:58.820
is about eight
times that for men.

00:53:58.820 --> 00:54:00.270
However, these
journeys have often

00:54:00.270 --> 00:54:02.990
been unchosen, one-way
trips in cultures that were

00:54:02.990 --> 00:54:05.090
patriarchal and patrilocal.

00:54:05.090 --> 00:54:07.010
That is, women were
under male control

00:54:07.010 --> 00:54:11.420
and also went to live in
their husbands households.

00:54:11.420 --> 00:54:15.550
In the face of all the dire
and often accurate warnings

00:54:15.550 --> 00:54:18.520
of danger on the
road for women, it

00:54:18.520 --> 00:54:22.760
took modern feminism to ask
the rock-bottom question,

00:54:22.760 --> 00:54:25.074
Compared to what?

00:54:25.074 --> 00:54:28.430
Whether it be by dowry
murders in India,

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:32.510
honor killings in Egypt,
domestic violence in United

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:35.360
States, records
show that women are

00:54:35.360 --> 00:54:37.170
most likely to be
beaten or killed

00:54:37.170 --> 00:54:39.900
at home and by men they know.

00:54:39.900 --> 00:54:45.040
Statistically speaking, home
is an even more dangerous place

00:54:45.040 --> 00:54:49.120
for women than on the road.

00:54:49.120 --> 00:54:51.580
Perhaps the most
revolutionary act for women

00:54:51.580 --> 00:54:54.510
will be a self-willed
journey and then

00:54:54.510 --> 00:54:58.420
be welcomed when she comes home.

00:54:58.420 --> 00:55:01.470
Nothing can sum my
experience better.

00:55:01.470 --> 00:55:03.790
We need to see one another.

00:55:03.790 --> 00:55:07.530
We need to hear from one
another with an open heart

00:55:07.530 --> 00:55:09.120
and an open mind.

00:55:09.120 --> 00:55:12.260
We need to learn
from one another.

00:55:12.260 --> 00:55:17.490
Someone says, You can't
survive the storm.

00:55:17.490 --> 00:55:23.580
